headline.main: Pregnant With a Boy? Even in 2014, Some Call That 'Lucky'

docs.abstract: I was pregnant: I didn’t want to engage people in a discussion on gender. I wanted to take a nap. Still, I was alarmed to hear repeatedly that it was somehow preferable to have a boy instead of a girl.
docs.snippet: I was pregnant: I didn’t want to engage people in a discussion on gender. I wanted to take a nap. Still, I was alarmed to hear repeatedly that it was somehow preferable to have a boy instead of a girl.

docs.lead_paragraph: What began as a largely American problem for Takata is taking on widening proportions, involving drivers and regulators in multiple countries.

headline.main: Defective Takata Airbag Grows Into Global Problem for Manufacturer
headline.print_headline: Defective Airbag Grows Into Global Problem for Manufacturer

docs.abstract: Faulty airbags from Japanese supplier Takata are problem that is taking on widening proportions, moving beyond American borders and involving drivers and regulators in multiple countries; one fatality has occurred in Malaysia, in addition to four previous deaths in United States; company's executives have shied away from addressing crisis.
docs.snippet: What began as a largely American problem for Takata is taking on widening proportions, involving drivers and regulators in multiple countries.

docs.lead_paragraph: The former wives of two players said they felt isolated and powerless when they were urged to stay quiet about violence and avoid causing disruptions.

headline.main: N.F.L. Was Family, Until Wives Reported Domestic Abuse
headline.kicker: Nowhere to Turn: Second of Two Articles
headline.print_headline: N.F.L. Was Family, Till Wives Reported Abuse
headline.content_kicker: Nowhere to Turn: Second of Two Articles

docs.abstract: Interviews with Mercedes Sands and Brandie Underwood, former wives of professional football players, reveal abusive relationships in which they felt trapped, in part because of sport's close-knit culture and disruption-minimizing protocol; outrage has grown over NFL's handling of domestic abuse cases, but little is heard from victims, in part because they often recant accusations, and stay with partners (Series: Nowhere to Turn).
docs.snippet: The former wives of two players said they felt isolated and powerless when they were urged to stay quiet about violence and avoid causing disruptions.

headline.main: Even the Democratic Caucus Can Fail to Accommodate Pregnancy

docs.abstract: Although it is primarily Democrats and President Obama who continue to push for the Pregnant Workers Fairness Act, a Democratic representative who is pregnant cannot get an exception on Democratic Caucus voting rules.
docs.snippet: Although it is primarily Democrats and President Obama who continue to push for the Pregnant Workers Fairness Act, a Democratic representative who is pregnant cannot get an exception on Democratic Caucus voting rules.

docs.lead_paragraph: Thaiya Spruill-Smith is technically dead but hooked up to machines because her mother wants her organs to help others, while her father says that would be a desecration.

headline.main: In Death, Girl, 2, Is Caught in Fight Over Organs
headline.print_headline: In Death, Girl, 2, Is Caught in Fight Over Organs

docs.abstract: Two-year-old Brooklyn girl Thaiya Spruill-Smith remains hooked up to machines despite having been declared legally dead two days earlier, amid dispute between her parents over organ donation; Teoka Spruill, her mother, wants daughter's organs to help other children, while Terrell Smith, her father, argues that it would be desecration; Spruill-Smith died two days after being violently shaken by David Adams, her stepfather.
docs.snippet: Thaiya Spruill-Smith is technically dead but hooked up to machines because her mother wants her organs to help others, while her father says that would be a desecration.

docs.lead_paragraph: A domestic abuse case involving Phillip Merling, a former Miami Dolphin, provides an example of lenient treatment of players by law enforcement agencies whose employees work off-duty jobs for football teams.

headline.seo: N.F.L. Teams’ Ties to Police Put Victims of Domestic Violence in a Bind
headline.main: Whisked Out of Jail, and Back to the N.F.L.
headline.kicker: Nowhere to Turn: First of Two Articles
headline.print_headline: Whisked Out of Jail, and Back to N.F.L.
headline.content_kicker: Nowhere to Turn: First of Two Articles

docs.abstract: Case of Phillip Merling, former Miami Dolphins defensive end who was arrested on domestic abuse charges in 2010, illustrates how special relationship between NFL teams and local law enforcement can lead to special treatment; Merling was allowed to leave jail through private exit and was escorted out by police commander who worked side jobs for Dolphins; issue has taken on new prominence amid scrutiny of NFL's treatment of players involved in domestic violence cases (Series: Nowhere to Turn).
docs.snippet: A domestic abuse case involving Phillip Merling, a former Miami Dolphin, provides an example of lenient treatment of players by law enforcement agencies whose employees work off-duty jobs for football teams.
